        "Description": {
            "val": "This line provides funding for mandatory safety design changes, cyber security remediation actions, habitability modifications, and obsolescence and reliability resolution to maintain LCS operational availability and achieve the full 25-year service life. Funding covers planned CNO availabilities and includes two years of planning costs and long lead time materials (LLTM).\n\nLN001 - Habitability Modification\nModifications to increase the permanent berths to 98 on the FREEDOM and INDEPENDENCE variants for LCS 11 and LCS 13-20. The change addresses the following additional racks in berthing spaces, increased refrigeration (chill and freeze), increased dry provision stores, increased potable water capability, increased solid waste storage, and laundry capability, to support the increase in core crew size from 40 to 50 personnel. \n\nLN002 - LCS Ships Class Safety Design Changes\nSafety modifications fund the redesigned stern ramp back-fit on five FREEDOM variant ships (LCS 11\/13\/15\/17\/19) to support 11M Rigid Hull Inflatable Boats (RHIB) operations and the installation of bridge wing for safe and effective operation of four INDEPENDENCE variant ships (LCS 14\/16\/18\/20). This funding also supports installation of the Man Overboard Indicator (MOBI) system on LCS 9-20. Note: Earlier ships changes were completed in prior years. Later ships will be corrected in-line. \n\nLN003 - LCS Modernization\nModernization funds back-fit and fact-of-life obsolescence changes on the Littoral Combat Ships (LCS) to include:\n- Mandatory Safety changes eliminate or reduce hazards to ship personnel or components. Safety considerations include human (includes human\/system interfaces), toxic\/hazardous materials and substances, testing, logistical support, weapons, and munitions\/explosives. \n- Cyber Security changes protect data and information processed by installed networks and information systems. This includes hardware, software, and firmware that provide integrity, confidentiality, non-repudiation, identification and authentication, and availability of shipboard systems.\n- Obsolescence changes are required to prevent systems from becoming incompatible with newer technologies, or to update systems.\n- Reliability changes are key to the LCS reaching its full operational capabilities for the 25 year service life. System and structural reliability modifications will increase the LCS Ao and performance, while decreasing maintenance costs."
        },
        "Justification": {
            "val": "LN001 - Habitability Modification\nModifications to increase the permanent berths to 98 on the FREEDOM and INDEPENDENCE variants for LCS 11 and LCS 13-20.\n\nLN002 - LCS Ships Class Safety Design Changes\nSafety modifications address the redesigned stern ramp back-fit on five FREEDOM variant ships (LCS 11\/13\/15\/17\/19) and  installation of bridge wing on four INDEPENDENCE variant ships (LCS 14\/16\/18\/20)\n\nLN003 - LCS Modernization\nModernization funds back-fit and fact-of-life obsolescence changes on the Littoral Combat Ships (LCS)"
        },
